Q: ASP.NET Core migrating database issue A: <p>For my case, this was the solution:</p>
<p>I adjusted the order of the code, made sure I added the controllers and DB context before building the app and it fixed the issue</p>
<p>Before</p>
<pre class="lang-cs prettyprint-override"><code>// Add services to the container
var app = builder.Build();

builder.Services.AddControllers();
builder.Services.AddDbContext&lt;AppDbContext&gt;(options =&gt; options.UseSqlite(dbPath));

app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
</code></pre>
<p>After</p>
<pre class="lang-cs prettyprint-override"><code>// Add services to the container
builder.Services.AddControllers();
builder.Services.AddDbContext&lt;AppDbContext&gt;(options =&gt; options.UseSqlite(dbPath));

var app = builder.Build();
app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
</code></pre>

Q: Set static property on static class in PowerShell A: <p>I've slightly misread your question and am reworking the answer as it should be possible.
I've thought your issue was you're trying to use <code>Add-Member</code> which is for edits of individual objects, when you want <code>Update-TypeData</code> since you're using classes.</p>
<p>Just an fyi, when attempting <code>Add-Member</code> on class instantiations it actually makes PSCustomObjects <em>wrapping your class object</em>, which you can end up pulling your hair out over wondering where your added values disappear to when passing to functions or [auto]casting (even to its own type..) as these can strip the wrapping away under a lot of conditions.</p>
<pre><code>class MyClass {
    #secret variable/s
    hidden $_PropertyName
    #public accessor/s
    hidden static $getters = @{
        PropertyName = {
            return $this._PropertyName
        }
    }
    #application of above
    static MyClass() {
        [MyClass]::getters.Keys `
        | %{
            Update-TypeData `
                -TypeName   ([MyClass].Name) `
                -MemberType 'ScriptProperty' `
                -MemberName $_ `
                -Value      ([MyClass]::getters[$_])
        }
    }

    MyClass() {
        $this._PropertyName = 'someValue'
    }

    Update() {
        $this._PropertyName = 'newValue'
    }
}

$test = [MyClass]::new()
$test.PropertyName = 'nope'  #readonly error
$test.PropertyName           #executes getter
$test.Update()               #update internally
$test.PropertyName           #check the change
$test | gm                   #hidden variable not *visible*
</code></pre>
<p><a href="https://i.sstatic.net/8kZULHTK.png" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.sstatic.net/8kZULHTK.png" alt="enter image description here" /></a></p>
<p>Just note that this isn't <em>secure</em>, if someone using your class knows <code>_PropertyName</code> exists, they <em>can</em> access it directly, and modify it. However this shouldn't be concerning, as no C# class is secure anyway;
